## Overview

The UI system provides a comprehensive framework for creating modal windows, dialogs, and UI elements with consistent styling. It supports multiple window layouts, content types, and styling options.

### Key Constants

- `MainWindowLayer = 125` - Layer for main windows
- `SideCarWindowLayer = 120` - Layer for sidebar windows

### Text Settings Presets

- `TextSettingsForHeaders` - Bold, large text for headers (size 60)
- `TextSettingsForButtons` - Auto-fitted text for buttons (16-48px)
- `TextSettingsForMessages` - Auto-fitted, word-wrapped text for messages (16-36px)

## Creating Windows

### Basic Window Creation

```csharp
var window = Window.Make(new WindowOptions() 
{
    Title = "My Window",
    WindowBackgroundStyle = WindowBackgroundStyle.Simple,
    WindowBackgroundColor = WindowBackgroundColor.Blue,
    Content = new CustomWindowContent()
    {
        DrawContent = (rect) => 
        {
            // Your custom UI code here
            UI.TextAsync(rect, "Hello World!", UI.TextSettingsForMessages);
        }
    }
});

// Draw the window (returns false when closed)
bool stayOpen = UI.DrawWindow(window);
```

### Window Options

All windows inherit from `WindowOptionsBase`:

```csharp
public class WindowOptions : WindowOptionsBase
{
    public string Title;                                      // Window title
    public AnimateType AnimateType;                           // None, Slide, or Scale
    public WindowTitleFlare WindowTitleFlare;                 // Title decoration
    public WindowBackgroundStyle WindowBackgroundStyle;       // Simple, SimpleWithBottomStripe, Blueprint, Rounded
    public WindowBackgroundColor WindowBackgroundColor;       // Black, Blue, Brown, Gold, Green, Grey, Orange, Purple, Red, White, Yellow
    public WindowHeaderColor WindowHeaderColor;               // Header color (MatchBackground or specific color)
    public WindowContent Content;                             // Window content (see below)
}
```

## Window Content Types

### 1. CustomWindowContent

Draw custom UI with full control:

```csharp
new CustomWindowContent()
{
    DrawContent = (rect) =>
    {
        // Draw whatever you want
        UI.Image(rect, myTexture);
        UI.TextAsync(rect, "Custom content", UI.TextSettingsForMessages);
    }
}
```

### 2. TabbedWindowContent

Create tabbed interfaces:

```csharp
new TabbedWindowContent()
{
    TabLocation = TabLocation.Top,           // Top or Side
    TabHeight = 60,                          // -1 for default
    SelectedTab = 0,                         // Initial tab
    TabButtonStyle = TabButtonStyle.Default, // Default, Simple, Shiny, Trapezoid
    TabButtonColor = ButtonColor.Grey,       // Inactive tab color
    TabSelectedButtonColor = ButtonColor.Orange, // Active tab color
    Tabs = new List<TabContent>()
    {
        new TabContent()
        {
            Label = "Tab 1",
            Icon = myTexture,  // Optional, used for side tabs
            Content = new CustomWindowContent() { /* ... */ }
        },
        new TabContent()
        {
            Label = "Tab 2",
            Content = new CustomWindowContent() { /* ... */ }
        }
    }
}
```

**Note**: Side tabs use icons instead of labels.

### 3. GridWindowContent

Display items in a grid layout:

```csharp
new GridWindowContent()
{
    Columns = 3,                  // Number of columns (-1 for default: 3)
    ItemHeight = 400,             // Height of each item (-1 for default: 400)
    DrawElementTabs = true,       // Draw tabs at bottom of items
    SelectedIndex = -1,           // Currently selected item (-1 for none)
    Items = new List<CollectionElement>()
    {
        new CollectionElement()
        {
            Label = "Item 1",
            Icon = itemTexture,
            Color = ElementColor.Blue,        // Blue, Green, Grey, Red, Rainbow, Yellow
            Style = ElementStyle.Simple,      // Simple, Banner, Banner2
            RarityStyle = RarityPipStyle.Star,      // None, Diamond, Pentagon, Star
            RarityColor = RarityPipColor.Gold,      // Various colors
            RarityPipLocation = RarityPipLocation.TopRight, // TopLeft, TopRight, BottomLeft, BottomRight
            Userdata = myCustomObject         // Store custom data
        }
    }
}
```

### 4. ListWindowContent

Display items in a vertical list:

```csharp
new ListWindowContent()
{
    ItemHeight = 200,             // Height of each item (-1 for default: 200)
    SelectedIndex = -1,           // Currently selected item
    Items = new List<CollectionElement>()
    {
        new CollectionElement()
        {
            Label = "Item Title",
            Description = "Item description text",
            Icon = itemTexture,
            Color = ElementColor.Blue,
            ListItemAction = (element) => 
            {
                // Action when button is clicked
                Console.WriteLine($"Clicked: {element.Label}");
            },
            ListItemActionButtonText = "Select",
            ListItemButtonColor = ButtonColor.Green,
            ListItemButtonStyle = ButtonStyle.Arrow
        }
    }
}
```

### 5. TreeWindowContent

Display items in a tree/grid with connections:

```csharp
new TreeWindowContent()
{
    NodeWidth = 125,
    NodeHeight = 125,
    RowSpacing = 25,
    ColumnSpacing = 50,
    SelectedNodeIndex = -1,
    Nodes = new List<TreeWindowNode>()
    {
        new TreeWindowNode()
        {
            Id = "node1",
            Row = 0,
            Column = 0,
            ConnectionState = TreeWindowNodeConnectionState.ConnectedEnabled, // None, Connected, ConnectedEnabled
            BackgroundColor = ButtonColor.Grey,
            SelectedBackgroundColor = ButtonColor.Blue,
            BackgroundStyle = ButtonStyle.Basic,
            ParentIds = null,  // No parent for root nodes
            Element = new CollectionElement()
            {
                Icon = nodeTexture
            }
        },
        new TreeWindowNode()
        {
            Id = "node2",
            Row = 1,
            Column = 0,
            ConnectionState = TreeWindowNodeConnectionState.Connected,
            ParentIds = new List<string>() { "node1" },  // Connect to parent
            Element = new CollectionElement() { Icon = nodeTexture }
        }
    }
}
```

**Connection Drawing**: Lines are automatically drawn from child nodes to their parents based on `ParentIds`.

### 6. ElementDisplayWindowContent

Display a single item with details:

```csharp
new ElementDisplayWindowContent()
{
    Element = new CollectionElement()
    {
        Label = "Item Name",
        Icon = largeTexture
    },
    Stats = new List<ElementStat>()
    {
        new ElementStat() { Text = "Attack: 50", Icon = attackIcon },
        new ElementStat() { Text = "Defense: 30", Icon = defenseIcon }
    },
    ButtonAction = (element) =>
    {
        // Action when button is clicked
    },
    ButtonText = "Equip",
    ButtonColor = ButtonColor.Orange,
    ButtonStyle = ButtonStyle.Basic,
    ItemUpdater = (content) => 
    {
        // Optional: Update the element dynamically each frame
        return updatedElement;
    }
}
```

### 7. SplitWindowContent

Split window into two regions:

```csharp
new SplitWindowContent()
{
    Axis = SplitAxis.Horizontal,  // Horizontal or Vertical
    SplitRatio = 0.5f,             // 0.0 to 1.0
    First = new CustomWindowContent() { /* ... */ },
    Second = new GridWindowContent() { /* ... */ }
}
```

### 8. SideCarWindowContent

Main content with sidebar:

```csharp
new SideCarWindowContent()
{
    Position = SideCarPosition.Right,  // Left or Right
    SideCarSize = new Vector2(400, 500),
    SideCarBackgroundColor = WindowBackgroundColor.Blue,
    SideCarBackgroundColorMultiplier = new Vector4(0.9f, 0.9f, 0.9f, 1),
    Main = new GridWindowContent() { /* ... */ },
    Side = new ElementDisplayWindowContent() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Styling Windows

### Window Background Styles

- `Simple` - Basic modal window
- `SimpleWithBottomStripe` - Modal with decorative bottom stripe
- `Blueprint` - Blueprint/schematic style
- `Rounded` - Rounded corners style

### Window Background Colors

Available colors: `Black`, `Blue`, `Brown`, `Gold`, `Green`, `Grey`, `Orange`, `Purple`, `Red`, `White`, `Yellow`

Blueprint-specific colors: `BlueprintBlue`, `BlueprintPink`, `BlueprintYellow`

### Title Flares

Add decorative banners to window titles:

```csharp
WindowTitleFlare = WindowTitleFlare.Gold  // None, Black, Blue, Green, Red, White, Yellow, Gold, Silver, Bronze
```

Gold, Silver, and Bronze flares include wreath decorations.

### Window Headers

Customize the header color separately from the background:

```csharp
WindowHeaderColor = WindowHeaderColor.Gold  // MatchBackground, or any color, or RoundedRed
```

## Buttons

### Drawing Buttons

Use `DrawWindowButton` for consistent button styling:

```csharp
var result = UI.DrawWindowButton(buttonRect, "Click Me", iconTexture, ButtonColor.Orange, ButtonStyle.Basic);
if (result.Pressed)
{
    // Button was clicked
}
```

### Button Styles

- `Basic` - Standard rectangular button
- `Arrow` - Button with arrow decoration
- `Skew` - Skewed/slanted button
- `BasicShiny` - Shiny rectangular button
- `ArrowShiny` - Shiny arrow button
- `SkewShiny` - Shiny skewed button

### Button Colors

Available colors: `Black`, `Blue`, `Brown`, `Green`, `Grey`, `Purple`, `Red`, `White`, `Yellow`, `Orange`

### Manual Button Creation

For more control:

```csharp
var result = UI.BeginButton(buttonRect, "MY_BUTTON_ID", new ButtonSettings(), new TextSettings());
{
    var buttonTexture = UI.GetButtonTexture(ButtonColor.Orange, ButtonStyle.Basic);
    var buttonSlice = UI.GetButtonSlice(ButtonColor.Orange, ButtonStyle.Basic);
    UI.Image(buttonRect, buttonTexture, buttonSlice);
    
    var textSettings = UI.TextSettingsForButtons;
    textSettings.OutlineColor = UI.ColorFromButtonColor(ButtonColor.Orange) * 0.7f;
    UI.TextAsync(buttonRect.Inset(25), "Click Me", textSettings);
}
UI.EndButton();

if (result.Clicked)
{
    // Handle click
}
```

## Alert Windows

Simple two-button dialogs:

```csharp
var result = UI.DrawAlertWindow(new AlertWindowOptions()
{
    Title = "Confirm Action",
    Message = "Are you sure you want to proceed?",
    WindowBackgroundColor = WindowBackgroundColor.Blue,
    WindowBackgroundStyle = WindowBackgroundStyle.Simple,
    
    AcceptButtonText = "Yes",
    AcceptButtonColor = ButtonColor.Green,
    AcceptButtonStyle = ButtonStyle.Basic,
    
    DeclineButtonText = "No",
    DeclineButtonColor = ButtonColor.Red,
    DeclineButtonStyle = ButtonStyle.Basic
});

switch (result)
{
    case AlertWindowResult.Accept:
        // User clicked accept
        break;
    case AlertWindowResult.Decline:
        // User clicked decline
        break;
    case AlertWindowResult.Close:
        // User clicked X button
        break;
    case AlertWindowResult.None:
        // Still open
        break;
}
```

## Examples

### Example 1: Simple Message Window

```csharp
var window = Window.Make(new WindowOptions()
{
    Title = "Welcome",
    WindowBackgroundStyle = WindowBackgroundStyle.Simple,
    WindowBackgroundColor = WindowBackgroundColor.Blue,
    WindowTitleFlare = WindowTitleFlare.Gold,
    Content = new CustomWindowContent()
    {
        DrawContent = (rect) =>
        {
            var textSettings = UI.TextSettingsForMessages;
            textSettings.Color = Vector4.White;
            UI.TextAsync(rect.Inset(50), "Welcome to the game!", textSettings);
        }
    }
});
```

### Example 2: Inventory Grid

```csharp
var window = Window.Make(new WindowOptions()
{
    Title = "Inventory",
    WindowBackgroundStyle = WindowBackgroundStyle.SimpleWithBottomStripe,
    WindowBackgroundColor = WindowBackgroundColor.Brown,
    Content = new GridWindowContent()
    {
        Columns = 4,
        ItemHeight = 300,
        Items = inventoryItems.Select(item => new CollectionElement()
        {
            Label = item.Name,
            Icon = item.Icon,
            Color = GetColorForRarity(item.Rarity),
            Style = ElementStyle.Banner,
            RarityStyle = RarityPipStyle.Star,
            RarityColor = GetRarityColor(item.Rarity),
            RarityPipLocation = RarityPipLocation.TopRight,
            Userdata = item
        }).ToList()
    }
});
```

### Example 3: Character Sheet with Tabs

```csharp
var window = Window.Make(new WindowOptions()
{
    Title = "Character",
    WindowBackgroundStyle = WindowBackgroundStyle.Simple,
    WindowBackgroundColor = WindowBackgroundColor.Blue,
    Content = new TabbedWindowContent()
    {
        TabLocation = TabLocation.Top,
        TabButtonStyle = TabButtonStyle.Shiny,
        TabButtonColor = ButtonColor.Grey,
        TabSelectedButtonColor = ButtonColor.Orange,
        Tabs = new List<TabContent>()
        {
            new TabContent()
            {
                Label = "Stats",
                Content = new CustomWindowContent()
                {
